<div class="answercell post-layout--right">
        <div class="js-endorsements" data-for-answer="4607299">
</div>

    
    <div class="s-prose js-post-body" itemprop="text">
<p>I had this same thought a while back as a purely academic interest. It's not directly possible to do what you're asking, although you are able to use PHP to produce PHP that then gets evaluated by the server.</p>
<p>Long story short:</p>
<h1>Don't bother</h1>
<p>Short story long:</p>
<ul>
<li>it adds a level of insecurity to your classing system as it becomes harder to control file access.</li>
<li>it slows down the compilation/caching of pages</li>
<li>you really don't need to force a square peg into a round hole.</li>
</ul>
<p>Instead: use proper OOP practices of separating functionality into classes and extending existing classes.</p>
    </div>
